MALARIA DETECTION FINAL SUBMISSION

Problem Definition¶

Malaria is a contagious disease caused by Plasmodium parasites that are transmitted to humans through the bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. Almost 50% of the world's population is in danger from malaria. There were more than 229 million malaria cases and 400,000 malaria-related deaths reported over the world in 2019. Children under 5 years of age are the most vulnerable population group affected by malaria; in 2019 they accounted for 67% of all malaria deaths worldwide. An automated system can help with the early and accurate detection of malaria.Applications of automated classification techniques using Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) have consistently shown higher accuracy than manual classification. It would therefore be highly beneficial to propose a method that performs malaria detection using Deep Learning Algorithms.

Objective:¶

To build an efficient computer vision model to detect malaria. The model should identify whether the image of a red blood cell is that of one infected with malaria or not, and classify the same as parasitized or uninfected, respectively.

Key Questions:¶

How malaria affects the red blood cells? The parasites enter the blood and begin damaging red blood cells (RBCs) that carry oxygen, which can result in respiratory distress and other complications. The lethal parasites can stay alive for more than a year h a person's body without showing any symptoms. Therefore, late treatment can cause complications and could even be fatal.

Problem Formulation:¶

It is a binary classification problem with mutually exclusive classes so will explore different Deep learning architectures and find the best one based on evaluation metrics.

Data Description ¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that we have taken from microscopic images. These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria
Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data which further contains the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

In [ ]:
# Storing the path of the extracted "train" folder 
train_dir = '/content/cell_images/train'

# Size of image so that each image has the same size
SIZE = 64

# Empty list to store the training images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
train_images = []

# Empty list to store the training labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
train_labels = []
In [ ]:
# We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    # Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
    
        try:
    
            # Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            # Resizing each image to (64, 64)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            # Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            # Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name == '/parasitized/':
            
                train_labels.append(1)
           
            else:
           
                train_labels.append(0)
        
        except Exception:
       
            pass       

# Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)

train_labels = np.array(train_labels)

Plotting the mean images for parasitized and uninfected

In [ ]:
# Function to find the mean
def find_mean_img(full_mat, title):

    # Calculate the average
    mean_img = np.mean(full_mat, axis = 0)[0]

    # Reshape it back to a matrix
    plt.imshow(mean_img)

    plt.title(f'Average {title}')

    plt.axis('off')

    plt.show()

    return mean_img

In [ ]:
# Creating sequential model
model = Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = 2, padding = "same", activation = "relu", input_shape = (64, 64, 3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = 2, padding = "same", activation = "relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = 2, padding = "same", activation = "relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))

model.add(Flatten())

model.add(Dense(512, activation = "relu"))
model.add(Dropout(0.4))
model.add(Dense(2, activation = "softmax")) # 2 represents output layer neurons 

model.summary()

Plotting the train and validation curves

In [ ]:
# Function to plot train and validation accuracy 
def plot_accuracy(history):

    N = len(history.history["accuracy"])

    plt.figure(figsize = (7, 7))

    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["accuracy"], label = "train_accuracy", ls = '--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["val_accuracy"], label = "val_accuracy", ls = '--')

    plt.title("Accuracy vs Epoch")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")

model2 = Sequential()

model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = 2))
model2.add(BatchNormalization(axis=-1))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))

Model 3 with Data Augmentation

In [ ]:
backend.clear_session() # Clearing backend for new model

Using image data generator

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(train_images, train_labels, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 42)

from keras.api._v2.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Using ImageDataGenerator to generate images
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True, zoom_range = 0.2, rotation_range = 30,
                                   shear_range=0.2, fill_mode='constant', width_shift_range=0.2, height_shift_range=0.2)

val_datagen  = ImageDataGenerator()

# Flowing training images using train_datagen generator
train_generator = train_datagen.flow(x = X_train, y = y_train, batch_size = 64, seed = 42, shuffle = True)


# Flowing validation images using val_datagen generator
val_generator =  val_datagen.flow(x = X_val, y = y_val, batch_size = 64, seed = 42, shuffle = True)

We will be checking if the performance of the model can be improved by changing different parameters in the ImageDataGenerator.¶

Visualizing Augmented images

In [ ]:
# Creating an iterable for images and labels from the training data
images, labels = next(train_generator)

# Plotting 16 images from the training data

fig.set_size_inches(10, 10)

    ax.imshow(image)

    if label[1] == 1: 

        ax.set_title('parasitized')

    else:

        ax.set_title('uninfected')

    ax.axis('off')

Observations and insights:

  • We can see that the images have been augmented going by the ImageDataGenerafor operation
  • ﻿﻿Training a model on augmented images might be more robust to slight changes/differences in the shape or intensity of the parasitized cells. Let's build a model with LeakyRelu as the activation function and some batch normalization layers.

Insights¶

  • The VGG16 model is not the best performance we have seen, compared with the other models, it might be possible that continuing to train it can slightly help it improve it's performance though we can say the model is performing alright with validation accuracy usually in the range of 97% and 93% training accuracy.
  • The lower training accuracy indicates that the model might give better results if we increase the complexity of the dense layers that we added or by increasing the number of epochs.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

Observations and Conclusions drawn from the final model and other models: _

  • We can observe that our model with add on layers ie model1 gives the best accuacy among all other models and its performance can be improved more
  • ﻿﻿Pretrained VGG16 model has an okay but not the best result.
  • ﻿﻿We built and evaluated multiple end-to-end deep learning models to improve malaria detection on the images. We applied different techniques like data augmentation, transfer learning in addition to the use of batch normalization technique which produced also a decent result.
  • ﻿﻿Our best model is the CNN model 1. Its has a slightly relatively less complex architecture than some of the other models, the accuracy on the validation set is not significantly higher than the accuracy of the trainning set, and the trainning loss is no much lower than the validation loss. It achieves an accuracy of 98.1% on the test data in classifying parasitized and uninfected cell images with the same high degree of precision and recall. . As an immediate extension of this work, we can try tuning the hyperparameters like optimizer, learning_rate, activation function, adding different layers to the architecture of the model. However we alreay have some good results and should avoid over tweaking or we may risk overfitting.
